128. 20. par et similis. These expressions are frequently used to· gether to express complete similarity in every respect. The difference between them is that par indicates the value, importance or power os a thing, similis its constitution, external or internal. Quintilian X, 1, 102 speaking of Sallust and Livy says that they were pares nragr's quom similes, ie. equal in worth, though different in character; and Seneca De Ira Ι, 9 speaking of the passions says: quos (affectus) neruiqunm deprimere possis, nisi pares illis similesque opposueris, ie. passions equally strong and like in kind.
